# Next.js Rules

## App Router
- Use the App Router (`app/` directory), not the Pages Router.
- Use Server Components by default. Only add `"use client"` when the component needs interactivity, hooks, or browser APIs.
- Colocate related files: `page.tsx`, `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, `layout.tsx` within route folders.

## Server vs Client Components
- Server Components: data fetching, database access, heavy computation, sensitive logic.
- Client Components: user interactions (onClick, onChange), React hooks (useState, useEffect), browser APIs.
- Keep Client Components as small as possible — extract interactive parts and keep the parent as a Server Component.
- Never import Server Components inside Client Components. Pass them as `children` instead.

## Data Fetching
- Fetch data in Server Components using `async/await` directly.
- Use `loading.tsx` for Suspense-based loading states.
- Use `error.tsx` for error boundaries per route segment.
- For client-side data, use TanStack Query (see data-fetching rules).

## API Routes
- Define API routes in `app/api/[route]/route.ts`.
- Always validate request body with Zod before processing.
- Return proper HTTP status codes and consistent error format:
```typescript
return NextResponse.json({ error: "Description" }, { status: 400 });
```
- Use `NextRequest` and `NextResponse` from `next/server`.

## Images & Fonts
- Use `next/image` for all images (automatic optimization).
- Use `next/font` for fonts (no layout shift).

## Metadata
- Use the `metadata` export or `generateMetadata` function for SEO.
- Always include title, description, and Open Graph tags on public pages.

## Environment Variables
- Server-only variables: `VARIABLE_NAME` (no prefix).
- Client-exposed variables: `NEXT_PUBLIC_VARIABLE_NAME`.
- Never expose secrets to the client.
